library(ttdviewer)

Below are examples of the data visualizations using inspectdf in the Shiny app.

Data

We’ll need data to demonstrate how the inspect_plot() function works. We’ll use the load_tt_data() function to collect four lists of data from the TidyTuesday repo.

"Netflix Titles" has a single dataset:

ttd <- load_tt_data("Netflix Titles")
#> INFO [2025-07-08 15:21:13] Starting import for netflix_titles.csv from https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/refs/heads/main/data/2021/2021-04-20/netflix_titles.csv
#> SUCCESS [2025-07-08 15:21:13] Successfully loaded netflix_titles.csv
purrr::map(.x = ttd, .f = attr, "clean_title")
#> $netflix_titles.csv
#> [1] "netflix_titles"
# for a list with two datasets, we'll use the `"Space Launches"` data

Utility functions

The inspect_plot() function has the following utility functions:

Check length

Check the length of the ttd3 list with ttd_length():

ttd_length(ttd = ttd3)
#> [1] 3

Check numeric columns

Check if datasets have numerical columns:

check_ttd_num_cols(ttd = ttd3)
#> $cpu.csv
#> [1] "transistor_count"     "date_of_introduction" "process"             
#> [4] "area"                
#> 
#> $gpu.csv
#> [1] "transistor_count"     "date_of_introduction" "process"             
#> [4] "area"                
#> 
#> $ram.csv
#> [1] "capacity_bits"        "transistor_count"     "date_of_introduction"
#> [4] "process"              "area"
  • If so, do they have two or more?

Check categorical columns

Check if datasets have categorical (character) columns:

check_ttd_cat_cols(ttd3)
#> $cpu.csv
#> [1] "processor" "designer" 
#> 
#> $gpu.csv
#> [1] "processor"      "designer_s"     "manufacturer_s" "ref"           
#> 
#> $ram.csv
#> [1] "chip_name"      "bit_units"      "ram_type"       "manufacturer_s"
#> [5] "ref"

Check list columns

Check list columns:

check_ttd_list_cols(ttd3)
#> $cpu.csv
#> [1] 0
#> 
#> $gpu.csv
#> [1] 0
#> 
#> $ram.csv
#> [1] 0

Check logical columns

Check logical columns:

check_ttd_log_cols(ttd3)
#> $cpu.csv
#> [1] 0
#> 
#> $gpu.csv
#> [1] 0
#> 
#> $ram.csv
#> [1] 0

Check date columns

Check date columns:

check_ttd_date_cols(ttd3)
#> $cpu.csv
#> [1] 0
#> 
#> $gpu.csv
#> [1] 0
#> 
#> $ram.csv
#> [1] 0

check_col_types()

These are wrapped in the check_col_types() function:

identical( # check the
  x = length(check_col_types(ttd = ttd3, type = "cat")),
  y = length(check_ttd_cat_cols(ttd3))
)
#> [1] TRUE
identical(
  x = length(check_col_types(ttd = ttd3, type = "date")),
  y = length(check_ttd_date_cols(ttd3))
)
#> [1] TRUE
identical(
  x = length(check_col_types(ttd = ttd3, type = "log")),
  y = length(check_ttd_log_cols(ttd3))
)
#> [1] TRUE
identical(
  x = length(check_col_types(ttd = ttd3, type = "num")),
  y = length(check_ttd_num_cols(ttd3))
)
#> [1] TRUE

The functions above allow us to collect the following:

  1. Determine the number of datasets in the ttd list
  2. Determine the name of the datasets in the ttd list
  3. Determine the number of numerical columns in each dataset in the ttd list
  4. Determine the names of any intersecting numerical columns in each dataset in the ttd list
  5. Determine the number of categorical columns in each dataset in the ttd list
  6. Determine the names of any intersecting categorical columns in each dataset in the ttd list
  7. Determine the number of logical columns in each dataset in the ttd list
  8. Determine the number of date columns in each dataset in the ttd list
  9. Determine the names of any date columns in each dataset in the ttd list
  10. Determine the number of list columns in each dataset in the ttd list
  11. Determine the names of any list columns in each dataset in the ttd list

Function logic

Using the functions above, write the custom inspect_plot() function and have it adhere to the following rules:

inspect_types()

if (length(ttd) == 1)

If one dataset in ttd:

inspectdf::inspect_cat(
  df1 = ttd2[[1]],
  df2 = NULL,
  include_int = TRUE
) |>
  inspectdf::show_plot(text_labels = TRUE)

if (length(ttd) == 2)

If two datasets in ttd:

  • check for intersecting columns
length(intersect(
  x = names(ttd2[[1]]),
  y = names(ttd2[[2]])
)) > 0
#> [1] TRUE
  • if columns intersect, store column names as intersecting_columns 
intersecting_columns <- intersect(x = names(ttd2[[1]]), y = names(ttd2[[2]]))
  • Then use intersecting_columns to subset ttd for the inspect_cat() function:
inspectdf::inspect_cat(
  df1 = ttd2[[1]][intersecting_columns],
  df2 = ttd2[[1]][intersecting_columns],
  include_int = TRUE
) |>
  inspectdf::show_plot(text_labels = TRUE)

if (length(ttd) >= 3)

If more than two datasets in ttd:

inspectdf::inspect_cat(
  df1 = ttd3[[1]],
  df2 = NULL,
  include_int = TRUE
) |>
  inspectdf::show_plot(text_labels = TRUE)

inspectdf::inspect_cat(
  df1 = ttd3[[2]],
  df2 = NULL,
  include_int = TRUE
) |>
  inspectdf::show_plot(text_labels = TRUE)

inspectdf::inspect_cat(
  df1 = ttd3[[3]],
  df2 = NULL,
  include_int = TRUE
) |>
  inspectdf::show_plot(text_labels = TRUE)

# ... for all datasets in ttd list

inspect_cor()

if (length(ttd) == 1)

If one dataset in ttd:

  • check if there are at least 2 numeric columns in the datasets in the ttd list
    • Plot the dataset with at least two numeric columns
if (ttd_length(ttd2) == 2) { # check for two datasets
  # check for two numerical columns in ttd[[1]]
  if (length(check_ttd_num_cols(ttd = ttd2)[[1]]) == 2) {
    # plot first dataset
    inspectdf::inspect_cor(
      df1 = ttd2[[1]],
      df2 = NULL,
      method = "pearson",
      with_col = NULL,
      alpha = 0.05
    ) |>
      inspectdf::show_plot(text_labels = TRUE)
    # check for two numerical columns in ttd[[2]]
  } else if (length(check_ttd_num_cols(ttd = ttd2)[[2]]) >= 2) {
    # plot second dataset
    inspectdf::inspect_cor(
      df1 = ttd2[[2]],
      df2 = NULL,
      method = "pearson",
      with_col = NULL,
      alpha = 0.05
    ) |>
      inspectdf::show_plot(text_labels = TRUE)
  } else {
    logr_msg("Error", level = "INFO")
  }
}

If two datasets in ttd:

Inspect plot

The inspect_plot() function will return all the relevant plots for the data contained the ttd list.

inspect_plot(ttd = ttd)
#> INFO [2025-07-08 15:21:51] inspect_plot(): starting analysis
#> INFO [2025-07-08 15:21:51] Beginning plot type 'types'

#> SUCCESS [2025-07-08 15:21:51] Completed plot type 'types'
#> INFO [2025-07-08 15:21:51] Beginning plot type 'mem'

#> SUCCESS [2025-07-08 15:21:52] Completed plot type 'mem'
#> INFO [2025-07-08 15:21:52] Beginning plot type 'na'

#> SUCCESS [2025-07-08 15:21:52] Completed plot type 'na'
#> INFO [2025-07-08 15:21:52] Beginning plot type 'cor'
#> SUCCESS [2025-07-08 15:21:52] Completed plot type 'cor'
#> INFO [2025-07-08 15:21:52] Beginning plot type 'imb'

#> SUCCESS [2025-07-08 15:21:53] Completed plot type 'imb'
#> INFO [2025-07-08 15:21:53] Beginning plot type 'num'
#> SUCCESS [2025-07-08 15:21:53] Completed plot type 'num'
#> INFO [2025-07-08 15:21:53] Beginning plot type 'cat'

#> SUCCESS [2025-07-08 15:21:55] Completed plot type 'cat'
#> SUCCESS [2025-07-08 15:21:55] inspect_plot(): all requested plots finished
#> NULL

It can also return specific graphs:

inspect_plot(ttd = ttd2, plot = "types")
#> INFO [2025-07-08 15:21:57] inspect_plot(): starting analysis
#> INFO [2025-07-08 15:21:57] Beginning plot type 'types'

#> SUCCESS [2025-07-08 15:21:58] Completed plot type 'types'
#> SUCCESS [2025-07-08 15:21:58] inspect_plot(): all requested plots finished
#> NULL
inspect_plot(ttd = ttd3, plot = "na")
